Name: Abul-Abbas
Note: An elephant given to Carolingian emperor Charlemagne by the Abbasid caliph Harun al-Rashid.

Name: Arjuna
Note: A lead elephant of the world-famous Mysore Dasara procession.

Name: Balarama
Note: A lead elephant of the world-famous Mysore Dasara procession.

Name: Black Diamond
Note: Believed to be the largest Indian elephant in captivity.

Name: Batyr
Note: An elephant claimed to be able to use a large amount of meaningful human speech, reported as having a vocabulary of more than 20 phrases.

Name: Chunee
Note: An elephant in the menagerie at Exeter Exchange, executed by soldiers from Somerset House in March 1826.

Name: Chengalloor Ranganathan
Note: Considered the tallest Asian thatever lived. He was killed by another elephant during Arattupuzha Festival in 1927. The century-old skeleton of this elephant is exhibited in the Thrissur Museum in the Main Entrance hall.

Name: The Cremona Elephant
Note: A gift presented to Holy Roman Emperor Frederick II by Sultan of Egypt Al-Kamil, in 1229. Frederick used the elephant in his triumph parades.

Name: Hanno
Note: The pet white elephant given by King Manuel I of Portugal to Pope Leo X at his coronation.

Name: Fanny
Note: A female elephant who spent the majority of her life in a small zoo.

Name: Hansken
Note: A female elephant that became famous in early 17th-century Europe. She toured many countries, demonstrating circus tricks, and was sketched by Rembrandt and Stefano della Bella.

Name: Hattie
Note: An elephant in New York City's Central Park Zoo that was described as the "most intelligent of all elephants" and "nearly human."

Name: Isilo
Note: One of South Africa’s largest Africans and the largest living tusker (a male elephant with tusks weighing over 100 pounds) in the southern hemisphere before his death.

Name: John L. Sullivan
Note: A boxing elephant in Adam Forepaugh's circus.

Name: Echo
Note: Most studied elephant in the world.

Name: Kashin
Note: Famous for being sponsored by ASB Bank, and featured in the New Zealand produced television programme The Zoo.

Name: Jumbo
Note: A 19th-century male African bush elephant born in Sudan. Jumbo was exported to Jardin des Plantes, a zoo in Paris, and then transferred in 1865 to London Zoo in England. Despite public protest, Jumbo was sold to P. T. Barnum, who took him to the United States for exhibition in March 1882.

Name: Kesavan
Note: Perhaps the most famous and celebrated temple elephant in Kerala, India. Keshavan was donated to the Guruvayur Hindu temple by the royal family of Nilambu.

Name: Kolakolli
Note: An Indian rogue elephant which gained considerable notoriety among Indian media and was accused of killing 12 people in and around Peppara over a span of seven to eight years.

Name: Lallah Rookh
Note: A female elephant known for her tightrope walking act.

Name: Drona
Note: The lead Dasara Elephants of the Jamboo Savari of Mysore Dasara. He carried the Golden Howdah for a record 18 years consecutive years between 1981 and 1997, before being electrocuted while grazing in 1998.

Name: Lin Wang
Note: Served with the Chinese Expeditionary Force during the Second Sino-Japanese War (1937–1945) and later relocated to Taiwan with the Kuomintang forces.

Name: Mary
Note: Also known as "Mighty Mary" and "Murderous Mary", this circus elephant was was hanged by a railroad derrick car after killing her inexperienced keeper. This is the only known elephant hanging in history.

Name: Miss Jim
Note: A former circus elephant, bought for the zoo by the children of St. Louis who pooled their pennies for her purchase.

Name: Motty
Note: Only confirmed Asian/African hybrid elephant.

Name: Mona
Note: Thought, at 60, to have been the oldest Asian in the United States.

Name: Packy
Note: First Asian born in the Western Hemisphere in 44 years.

Name: Old Bet
Note: The first circus elephant and the second elephant brought to the United States.

Name: Queenie
Note: A captive female Asian which was noted in the late 1950s and early 1960s for waterskiing for entertainment.

Name: Raja Gaj
Note: Considered to be the world's largest Asian of modern times.

Name: Raja
Note: A Sri Lankan tusker elephant which participated at the annual Esala procession in Kandy for around 50 years, and was declared as a national treasure, in recognition of his valuable services to the religion and culture of Sri Lanka.

Name: Osama bin Laden
Note: Rogue elephant which killed at least 27 people in India from 2004 to 2006.

Name: Rajje
Note: A performing elephant that escaped into the streets of Lansing, Michigan, and was killed by gunfire.

Name: Ruby
Note: An elephant famous for creating paintings. The most expensive of her paintings sold for $25,000.

Name: Rosie
Note: An instrumental figure in the history of the U.S. city of Miami Beach, Florida. Her appearance in publicity photos helped to contribute to the area's early reputation for being a place that a visitor had to see to believe.

Name: Salt
Note: Salt and Sauce were once two of Britain's most famous and notorious performing elephants. Sauce killed her owner and trainer in an accident at Walthamstow Station and Salt killed an elephant groom when she attacked him in 1957 on Rosaire's Circus.

Name: Queenie
Note: Gave rides for children at Melbourne Zoo for 40 years.

Name: Sauce
Note: Salt and Sauce were once two of Britain's most famous and notorious performing elephants. Sauce killed her owner and trainer in an accident at Walthamstow Station and Salt killed an elephant groom when she attacked him in 1957 on Rosaire's Circus.

Name: Thiruvambadi Sivasundar
Note: An Indian elephant purchased by businessman Sundar Menon who gave him as an offering to the deity at the Thiruvambadi Sri Krishna Temple.

Name: Tai
Note: Known for featuring in the films Larger than Life and Water for Elephants.

Name: Suleiman
Note: Presented in 1551 to Maximilian II, the Holy Roman Emperor, by John III, the King of Portugal, and named after the Ottoman Sultan, Suleiman the Magnificent.

Name: Topsy
Note: Killed a spectator who burned her trunk with a lit cigar. In 1903 the owners of a Coney Island park where she ended up publicly executed her via poison, electrocution, and strangling. The Edison Manufacturing movie company shot a film of the execution called Electrocuting an Elephant.

Name: Surus
Note: Mentioned as the bravest of Hannibal's 37 war elephants which crossed the Alps in 218 BC during the Second Punic War, by Cato the Elder in his book Origines.

Name: Tuffi
Note: A female circus elephant that became famous in Germany during 1950 when she accidentally fell into the River Wupper, and survived.

Name: Tyke
Note: A circus elephant who killed her trainer Allen Campbell and injured her groom Dallas Beckwith before hundreds of spectators. She then bolted from the arena and ran through downtown streets for more than 30 minutes. Police fired 86 shots at Tyke, who eventually collapsed from the wounds and died.

Name: Ziggy
Note: After attacking and nearly killing his keeper, Ziggy was chained to the wall of an indoor enclosure, and remained there for nearly three decades. In the late 1960s, when school children and other animal enthusiasts began campaigning for his release, eventually winning the case.

Name: Satao
Note: One of Kenya's largest Africans, which had unusually large tusks and was killed by poachers.
